properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for West and South Gippsland.
  • A high risk of epidemic thunderstorm asthma is forecast for West and South Gippsland today.
  • The peak period of concern is from 5pm today.
  • People may experience asthma symptoms or difficulty breathing due to thunderstorm activity.
  • Thunderstorm asthma can be triggered by a combination of high amounts of grass pollen in the air and a certain type of thunderstorm. For people who have asthma or hay fever this, can trigger severe asthma symptoms.
Be aware of an increased chance of experiencing breathing difficulties or an asthma attack. Prepare now - carry your asthma reliever puffer with you at all times today.

What you should do:

What you should do:

  • Avoid the wind gusts before the storm. Go inside and close your windows and doors.
  • Turn off air conditioners that bring in air from the outside (ie evaporative air conditioners).
  • Be aware of and act on the development of asthma symptoms including wheezing, breathlessness, tightness in the chest, or a persistent cough, as you may be having an asthma attack.
  • An asthma attack is serious and can be life threatening.
If you are experiencing asthma symptoms for the first time:
  • Don’t ignore them; use the four steps of asthma first aid.
  • If you don’t have an asthma reliever puffer, they are available without a prescription from pharmacies.
  • You can also use another person’s asthma reliever if available.
  • If your asthma suddenly becomes worse or is not improving, or if you are having an asthma attack and a reliever is not available, call Triple Zero (000) immediately.
For health advice:
  • Call Triple Zero (000) immediately if someone is not breathing, if their asthma suddenly becomes worse or is not improving, or if the person is having an asthma attack and an asthma reliever puffer is not available.
  • Call Nurse on Call on 1300 60 60 24 or see your doctor if you require medical advice.
Impacts in your area:
  • The high risk of epidemic thunderstorm asthma is due to an unexpected storm, which is forecast to occur from 5pm.
This message was issued by the Department of Health .

The next update is expected by 30/10/2023 08:30 pm or as the situation changes.

For more information:
  • For more information on what thunderstorm asthma is, visit the Better Health Channel.
  • Monitor epidemic thunderstorm asthma forecasts.
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#thunderstormasthma)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham.

The main flood peak along the Murray River has passed Barham, where river levels peaked overnight Wednesday into Thursday, with minor flooding. River levels are slowly easing.   

River levels at Swan Hill and downstream are expected to remain below minor flood levels.

The Murray River at Barham peaked at 5.70 metres overnight Wednesday 25 October and is currently at 5.67 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Murray River at Barham is likely to remain above the minor flood level (5.50 m) over the weekend into early next week.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • River levels at Swan Hill and downstream are expected to remain below minor flood levels.
  • Several roads are closed in Gunbower State Forest and National Park due to heavy rain and high flows of the Murray River. Check for closures on the FFMVic interactive Public Access Map.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • This warning is for communities in Victoria. Floods have different impacts on either side of the Murray River. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, visit www.hazardwatch.gov.au. Always follow advice from your State’s emergency services.
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
